ore fraught and can lead to difficult, often unsatisfying compromises regarding how to interpret and inhabit our public lands and spaces. A serious commitment to secularism, Howe shows, forces us to confront the profound challenges of true religious diversity in ways that often will have their ultimate expression in our built environment. This provocative exploration of some of the fundamental aspects of American life will help us see the land, law, and society anew.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChurch and statezUnited States. 0aCultural landscapeszUnited States. 0aEnvironmentalismxReligious aspects. 0aLandscapesxReligious aspects. 0aReligion and lawzUnited States. 0aReligion and statezUnited States. 0aSecularismzUnited States. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aenvironment.  ageography.  alandscape.  alaw.  asecularity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022637677640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226376806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226376806/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles